content.text: Five things to watch at the Trump-Xi summit

Donald Trump and Xi Jinping will hold their first summit in Florida on Thursday and Friday, with the US and Chinese presidents set to discuss everything from trade to the North Korean nuclear threat. US officials have played down the potential for breakthroughs on contentious issues and stressed that the meeting is aimed at starting a relationship and setting a framework for future talks. But Mr Trump told the Financial Times last week in an interview that he "would not be at all surprised if we did something that would be very dramatic and good for both countries". Here's what to watch over the next two days.
North Korea
Mr Trump has made North Korea his most pressing national security issue after Barack Obama warned him about the progress Pyongyang had made towards being able to hit the US with a nuclear-armed missile. Mr Trump told the FT he would urge Mr Xi to put more pressure on North Korea to halt its nuclear programme but said he was prepared to act unilaterally . One US official said Mr Xi's response would be "in some ways a test of the relationship" between Washington and Beijing.
North Korea fired a missile into the Sea of Japan on Wednesday ahead of the summit — in a similar way that it tested a missile while Mr Trump was hosting Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe at Mar-a-Lago in February. On Wednesday, the Chinese foreign ministry said there was "no connection" between the latest missile test and the Florida summit. China has consistently tried to position itself as an "honest broker" between Pyongyang and Washington, likening them to two trains racing towards a collision.
But this "moral equivalency" argument has angered US officials, who reject China's assertion that the US and South Korea are as much to blame for the crisis as North Korea. They say Pyongyang's pursuit of long-range missiles has dramatically altered the security situation on the Korean peninsula, requiring China to take a much tougher stance with its neighbour and ally.
Taiwan
Chinese officials were shocked when Mr Trump broke with four decades of precedent in December by speaking to Taiwanese president Tsai Ing-wen and later suggesting he might not abide by the "One China" policy under which Washington recognises Beijing as the sole seat of the Chinese government. While Mr Trump backed down from that threat in a February phone call with Mr Xi, any sign of another reversal would be hugely embarrassing for his guest. Susan Thornton, the top state department Asia official, said this week the Chinese might raise the issue but that Mr Trump would reaffirm his support for the policy.
Trade and investment
Mr Trump talked tough about China and trade during his campaign. But he has so far not followed through on his threat to declare China a "currency manipulator" and to slap punitive tariffs on Chinese imports, suggesting that less hawkish members of his administration have convinced him not to launch a trade war at the start of his first term. Mr Trump told the FT he wanted China to cut its tariffs but would not raise the issue in their first summit.
But Wilbur Ross, US commerce secretary, has hinted that tough new measures are needed to combat what Washington sees as unfair trade practices. In an effort to forestall trade friction, Mr Xi could promise more Chinese investment in US infrastructure and manufacturing. But while Chinese investment in the US more than tripled last year to $45bn, the vast majority came from private sector entrepreneurs.
China's traditional preference for large, multibillion "state-to-state" investments by government-controlled companies in overseas infrastructure projects would be politically controversial in the US. Underscoring the sensitivities, however, senior Trump administration officials are actively trying to find a buyer for US nuclear engineering group Westinghouse to ensure the bankrupt company, currently owned by Japan's Toshiba, does not fall into Chinese hands .
South China Sea
Mr Trump has followed Mr Obama in being very critical of China's territorial claims in the South China Sea. But Rex Tillerson, his secretary of state, said in January that Chinese ships and aircraft should be "denied access" to recently completed island fortifications, which suggests the Trump administration might take a tougher line than the Obama administration. However, James Mattis, US defence secretary, played down these tensions on his first visit to Asia in February, and Chinese officials hope Mr Trump will not repeat his earlier criticisms — which some US officials believe would be counterproductive at a time when Washington wants Beijing to help it more with the threat from North Korea.
What little confidence China had in Mr Trump's ability to restrain himself, however, was undermined last week when, just hours after Beijing confirmed that Mr Xi would travel to Florida, Mr Trump predicted a "very difficult" meeting with his Chinese counterpart. But in comments that highlighted his tendency to send mixed signals, he told the FT in its interview that he had "great respect" for Mr Xi and China.
Mar-a-Lago theatre
China appreciated the decision to host Mr Xi at Mar-a-Lago, instead of at the White House, as the move conveys the importance of the Chinese leader, particularly after Mr Trump hosted Mr Abe for three days at the resort. While Mr Trump and Mr Abe appeared to hit it off, US and Chinese officials are both nervous about how the Trump-Xi relationship will develop.
While Mr Xi is getting the red carpet, he is not receiving the same treatment as Mr Abe who dined with Mr Trump on at least four occasions after flying down to Florida on Air Force One. He will also not enjoy one of the pleasures that Mr Abe had in West Palm Beach — a round of golf with the president.
"I think it's safe to say there's not going to be any golf," said one US official, referring obliquely to the fact that Mr Xi has cracked down on party officials playing golf as part of his anti-corruption campaign. "It's possible that they'll walk around a bit, as the mood strikes, but nothing formal or nothing involving golf clubs."
